model_explanation: the prosodic focus is on "ROB," meaning Sam gave bananas to Rob and no one else. Therefore, it is entailed that Sam didn’t give bananas to Tom or anyone else.

the prosodic focus is on "TOM," meaning Sam gave grapes to Tom and no one else. This doesn’t specify what else Tom may have received, but since it focuses on grapes to Tom only, it implies that grapes—not oranges—were given to Tom.

the prosodic focus is on "SUE," meaning Sam only gave oranges to Sue and not to anyone else. The second sentence contradicts this by saying Sue also got apples, which violates the exclusivity implied by “only” in S1.
the prosodic focus is on "SUE," meaning Sam gave bananas exclusively to Sue and no one else. Therefore, it is entailed that Sam did not give bananas to Rob.
the prosodic focus is on "TOM," meaning Sam gave oranges to Tom and no one else. This means Tom did not receive anything else, including bananas. So the sentences are entailed.
the prosodic focus is on "SUE," meaning Sam gave apples to Sue and no one else. That means Sue didn’t get any other kind of fruit, including oranges.
the prosodic focus is on "GRAPES," meaning Sue only received grapes and nothing else. Therefore, it is entailed that Sue didn’t receive apples.
the prosodic focus is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave oranges exclusively to Ellen. That excludes that Ellen received anything else, so the claim that Ellen also got bananas is a contradiction.

the prosodic focus is on "MARY," meaning Mary exclusively got grapes. While we know Mary didn’t get anything else but grapes, that doesn’t directly speak to whether she got apples specifically. The independence of focus makes the statements independent.
the prosodic focus is on "BILL," meaning Sam gave oranges only to Bill and no one else. Therefore, the statement that Mary also got oranges contradicts this.
